SUMMARY:Finn: A New Musical- At the PB&J Cafe
DTSTART;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260503T130000
DTEND;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260503T140000
UID:ai1ec-140265-90582@wfhb.org
DESCRIPTION:Constellation Stage & Screen presents “Finn: A New Musical- 
 At the PB&J Cafe\,” on stage May 1-17 at the Waldron Auditorium.From the
  creator of Doc McStuffins and Vampirina\, Finn is a heartwarming musical 
 adventure about a young shark on the brink of growing up. As he prepares t
 o join the fearsome Shark Guard\, Finn can’t shake the feeling that he
 ’s different from the other sharks. Deep inside\, he discovers a colorfu
 l fish inside him—a part of himself that longs to sparkle\, sing\, and d
 ance. As Finn embarks on a journey of self-discovery\, friendship\, and ad
 venture\, he finds the courage to be himself! Fun for all ages!PB&J Cafe: 
 A Dinner Theater for Kids! At the PB&J Cafe\, young theatergoers will enjo
 y a meal during the performance and leave with autographs from their favor
 ite characters.
LOCATION:Waldron Arts Center (122 S Walnut St)
URL:https://wfhb.org/event/finn-a-new-musical-at-the-pbj-cafe-2/?instance_
 id=90582
X-SOURCE:WFHB Community Calendar
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Lincoln’s Declaration: How He Interpreted–and Defended–Our F
 ounding Document
DTSTART;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260503T140000
DTEND;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260503T153000
UID:ai1ec-144515-92913@wfhb.org
DESCRIPTION:To honor its 250th Anniversary\, John Schilb\, Culbertson Chai
 r and Professor Emeritus of English\, will analyze Abraham Lincoln’s rhe
 toric regarding the Declaration of Independence. Many of Lincoln’s oppon
 ents (e.g.\, Stephen Douglas and Jefferson Davis) either ridiculed the Dec
 laration’s claim that “all men are created equal” or believed that i
 t applied just to whites. Lincoln maintained that “all” really did mea
 n everyone. Only gradually\, however\, was he willing to consider Black pe
 ople his social peers. Statements that he made during his debates with Dou
 glas reflect this complex attitude. And even the Gettysburg Address does n
 ot assume that the Declaration’s message has a future. Indeed\, that spe
 ech called the Declaration’s claim about equality a “proposition” to
  be tested. That is\, Lincoln saw American democracy as something that mig
 ht not endure. Its fate still seems in question\, so his take on the Decla
 ration remains timely.
LOCATION:Unitarian Universalist Church of Bloomington\, 2120 N. Fee Lane\,
  Bloomington
URL:https://wfhb.org/event/lincolns-declaration-how-he-interpreted-and-def
 ended-our-founding-document/?instance_id=92913
X-SOURCE:WFHB Community Calendar
END:VEVENT
